<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-486-532  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 486 532.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer-Aided Engineering  July 1989 v8 n7 pS16(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>CAD/CAM basics.andM;</TITLE><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Computer-aided design and computer-aided engineering (CAD-CAM)consist of a range of hardware and software tools for design,drafting, analysis, engineering, and testing, and the control andintegration of manufacturing tools and tasks.andP;  These are allintegrated under the aegis and linking of computer-integratedmanufacturing (CIM).andP;  CAD-CAM systems consist of computerhardware, peripherals, engineering software, manufacturingsystems, and networks.andP;  Computers may be in the form ofmicrocomputers, workstations, and multi-user hosts with terminals.andO;Major peripherals include graphics entry devices and hardcopyoutput units.andP;  Engineering software includes design, analysis, andCAM factory systems, the latter exemplified by numerical controland automated device programs and manufacturing resource planningpackages.andP;  CAD-CAM systems integration and expansion aredescribed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CAD-CAMComputer-Aided DesignComputer-Aided ManufacturingSystem SelectionCriteriaSystem DesignIntegrated Systems.andO;Feature:   illustrationcharttable.andO;Caption:   Demands for CAD-CAM connectivity by mainframe and desktop users.andO;(chart)Basic CAD-CAM networks allow users to exchange data and useelectronic mail. (chart)Systems integration puts the pieces together. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>